# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrolytic-capacitor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] It is usually done as products leave the factory, or in some cases even within the factory.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Most often a producer supplies a consumer with several items and a decision to accept or reject the items is made by determining the number of defective items in a sample from the lot.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] The lot is accepted if the number of defects falls below where the acceptance number or otherwise the lot is rejected.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] A wide variety of acceptance sampling plans is available.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] For example, multiple sampling plans use more than two samples to reach a conclusion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] A shorter examination period and smaller sample sizes are features of this type of plan.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Although the samples are taken at random, the sampling procedure is still reliable.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Acceptance sampling procedures became common during World War II.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Sampling plans, such as MIL-STD-105, were developed by Harold F.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Dodge and others and became frequently used as standards.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] More recently, quality assurance broadened the scope beyond final inspection to include all aspects of manufacturing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Broader quality management systems include methodologies such as statistical process control, HACCP, six sigma, and ISO 9000.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Some use of acceptance sampling still remains.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Sampling provides one rational means of verification that a production lot conforms to the requirements of technical specifications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] 100% inspection does not guarantee 100% compliance and is too time-consuming and costly.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Rather than evaluating all items, a specified sample is taken, inspected or tested, and a decision is made about accepting or rejecting the entire production lot.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Sampling plans have known risks: an acceptable quality limit (AQL) and a rejectable quality level, such as lot tolerance percent defective (LTDP), are part of the operating characteristic curve of the sampling plan.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] These are primarily statistical risks and do not necessarily imply that a defective product is intentionally being made or accepted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Plans can have a known average outgoing quality limit (AOQL).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] A single sampling plan for attributes is a statistical method by which the lot is accepted or rejected on the basis of one sample.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Suppose that we have a lot of sizes M ; a random sample of size $N<M$ is selected from the lot; and an acceptance number B is determined.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] If it is found the number of nonconforming is less than or equal to B , the lot is accepted; and if the number of nonconforming is greater than B , the lot is not accepted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] The design of a single sampling plan requires the selection of the sample size N and the acceptance number B .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] MIL-STD-105 was a United States defense standard that provided procedures and tables for sampling by attributes (pass or fail characteristic).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] MIL-STD-105E was cancelled in 1995 but is available in related documents such as ANSI/ASQ Z1.4, "Sampling Procedures and Tables for Inspection by Attributes." Several levels of inspection are provided and can be indexed to several AQLs.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] The sample size is specified and the basis for acceptance or rejection (number of defects) is provided.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] MIL-STD-1916 is currently the preferred method of sampling for all Department of Defense (DoD) contracts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] When a measured characteristic produces a number, other sampling plans, such as those based on MIL-STD-414, are often used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/acceptance-sampling] Compared with attribute sampling plans, these often use a smaller sample size for the same indexed AQL.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The company's initial focus was driven by electrical lighting, as in 1881, Rathenau had acquired the rights to the electric light bulb at the International Exposition of Electricity in Paris.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Using small power stations, his company introduced electrical lighting to cafés, restaurants, and theaters, despite the high costs and limitations.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] By the end of the 19th century, AEG had constructed 248 power stations, providing a total of 210,000 hp of electricity for lighting, tramways, and household devices.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG worked with the Nazi Party and benefited from forced labor in Nazi concentration camps.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] After the war, its headquarters moved to Frankfurt am Main.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1967, AEG joined with its subsidiary Telefunken.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1985, Daimler-Benz purchased AEG and wholly integrated the company in 1996.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The remains of AEG became part of Adtranz and Deutsche Aerospace.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] After acquiring the AEG household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, Electrolux obtained the rights to the AEG brand name in 2005, which it now uses on some of its products.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The AEG name is also licensed to various brand partners under the Electrolux Global Brand Licensing program.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1883, Emil Rathenau founded Deutsche Edison-Gesellschaft für angewandte Elektricität in Berlin.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1888, it was renamed as Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Initially producing electrical equipment (such as light bulbs, motors, and generators), the company soon became involved in AC electric-transmission systems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1907, Peter Behrens was appointed as artistic consultant to AEG.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] This led to the creation of the company's initial corporate identity, with products and advertising sharing common design features.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The company expanded in the first half of the 20th century, and it is credited with a number of firsts and inventions in electrical engineering.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] During the same period, it entered the automobile and airplane markets.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Electrical equipment for railways was produced during this time, beginning a long history of supplying the German railways with electrical equipment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] During the Second World War, AEG joined with other large companies such as IG Farben, Thyssen, and Krupp in their support of the Nazis.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The company benefited from the use of large numbers of forced labourers, as well as concentration-camp prisoners, under inhuman conditions of work.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] After WWII, the company lost its businesses in the eastern part of Germany.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] After a merger in 1967, the company was renamed Allgemeine Elektricitäts-Gesellschaft AEG-Telefunken, and from 1979 on, only as AEG-Telefunken.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The company experienced financial difficulties during the 1970s, resulting in the sale of some assets.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1983, the consumer electronics division Telefunken Fernseh und Rundfunk was sold.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1985, the company retook the name AEG and the remainder of the company was acquired by Daimler-Benz; the parts that remained were primarily related to electric power distribution and electric motor technology.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Under Daimler-Benz ownership, the former AEG companies eventually became part of the newly named Adtranz in 1995, and the AEG name was no longer used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Electrolux, which had already acquired the household subsidiary AEG Hausgeräte in 1994, now own the rights to use and license the AEG brand.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The company originated in 1882, when Emil Rathenau acquired licences to use some of Thomas Edison's lamp patents in Germany.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The Deutsche Edison Gesellschaft ("German Edison Company") was founded in 1883 with the financial backing of banks and private individuals, with Emil Rathenau as company director.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1884, Munich-born engineer Oskar von Miller (who later founded Deutsches Museum) joined the executive board.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The same year, the company entered negotiations with the Berlin Magistrat (the municipal body) to supply electricity to a large area from a central supply, which resulted in the formation of the Städtischen Elektrizitätswerke (A.G.StEW) ("City electricity works company (Berlin)") on 8 May 1884.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] The original factory was located near Stettiner Bahnhof.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1887, the company acquired land in the Berlin-Gesundbrunnen area on which the Weddingsche Maschinenfabrik (founded by Wilhelm Wedding) was previously located.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In the same year, in addition to a restructuring and expansion of the production range, the AEG name was adopted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1887, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrowolsky joined the company as chief engineer, later becoming vice-director.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] His work on polyphase electric power led him to become the world's leading engineer in three-phase electric power systems at the end of the 1880s.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] This success marked one of beginnings of the general use of alternating current for electrification in Germany, and showed that distance transmission of electric power could be economically useful.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In the same year, the Stadtbahn Halle/Saale (City railway Halle–Saale) opened the first electric tram system (of notable size) in Germany.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] Tropp Paul began his work for the AEG from 1889/90 until 1893, and Franz Schwechten designed the facades of the Acker- und Hussitenstraße in 1894–95.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aeg-german-company] In 1894, the site of the former Berlin Viehmarktgasse (cattle market alley) was purchased.
