[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Heeger was elected as a member into the National Academy of Engineering in 2002 for co-founding the field of conducting polymers and for pioneering work in making these novel materials available for technological applications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Heeger was born in Sioux City, Iowa, into a Jewish family.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] He grew up in Akron, Iowa, where his father owned a general store.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] At age nine, following his father's death, the family moved back to Sioux City.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Heeger earned a B.S. in physics and mathematics from the University of Nebraska in 1957, and a Ph.D in physics from the University of California, Berkeley in 1961.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] From 1962 to 1982 he was on the faculty of the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] In 1982 he commenced his present appointment as a professor in the Physics Department and the Materials Department at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] His research has led to the formation of numerous start-up companies including Uniax, Konarka, and Sirigen, founded in 2003 by Guillermo C.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Alan Heeger was a founder of Uniax, which was acquired by DuPont.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] He won the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 2000 along with Alan G.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] MacDiarmid and Hideki Shirakawa "for their discovery and development of conductive polymers"; They published their results on polyacetylene a conductive polymer in 1977.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] This led to the construction of the Su–Schrieffer–Heeger model, a simple model for topological insulators.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Buckley Prize of the American Physical Society in 1983 and, in 1995, the Balzan Prize for Science of Non-Biological Materials.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] His sons are the neuroscientist David Heeger and the immunologist Peter Heeger.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] In October 2010, Heeger participated in the USA Science and Engineering Festival's Lunch with a Laureate program where middle and high school students engage in an informal conversation with a Nobel Prize-winning scientist over a brown-bag lunch.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Heeger is also a member of the USA Science and Engineering Festival's Advisory Board.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] Heeger has been a judge of the *STAGE* International Script Competition three times (2006, 2007, 2010).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] "Perhaps the greatest pleasure of being a scientist is to have an abstract idea, then to do an experiment (more often a series of experiments is required) that demonstrates the idea was correct; that is, Nature actually behaves as conceived in the mind of the scientist.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] This process is the essence of creativity in science.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-j-heeger] I have been fortunate to have experienced this intense pleasure many times in my life." Alan J Heeger, Never Lose Your Nerve!
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid was born in Masterton, New Zealand, as one of five children – three brothers and two sisters.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] His family was relatively poor, and the Great Depression made life difficult in Masterton, due to which his family shifted to Lower Hutt, a few miles from Wellington, New Zealand.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] At around age ten, he developed an interest in chemistry from one of his father's old textbooks, and he taught himself from this book and from library books.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid was educated at Hutt Valley High School and Victoria University of Wellington.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] In 1943, MacDiarmid passed the University of New Zealand's University Entrance Exam and its Medical Preliminary Exam.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He then took up a part-time job as a "lab boy" or janitor at Victoria University of Wellington during his studies for a BSc degree, which he completed in 1947.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He was then appointed demonstrator in the undergraduate laboratories.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] After completing an MSc in chemistry from the same university, he worked as an assistant in its chemistry department.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] It was here that he had his first publication in 1949, in the scientific journal *Nature*.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He graduated in 1951 with first class honours, and won a Fulbright Fellowship to the University of Wisconsin–Madison.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He majored in inorganic chemistry, receiving his M.S. degree in 1952 and his PhD in 1953.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He then won a Shell Graduate Scholarship, which enabled him to go to Sidney Sussex College, Cambridge, where he completed a second PhD in 1955.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid worked in the School of Chemistry at the University of St Andrews in Scotland for a year as a member of the junior faculty.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He then took a faculty position in chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania, United States, where he became a full professor in 1964.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid spent the greater part of his career on the chemistry faculty of the University of Pennsylvania, where he worked for 45 years.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] The first twenty years of his research there focused on silicon chemistry.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He was appointed Blanchard Professor of Chemistry in 1988.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] In 2002 MacDiarmid also joined the faculty of the University of Texas at Dallas.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] His best-known research was the discovery and development of conductive polymers—plastic materials that conduct electricity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He collaborated with the Japanese chemist Hideki Shirakawa and the American physicist Alan Heeger in this research and published the first results in 1977.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] The three of them shared the 2000 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for this work.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] The Nobel Prize was awarded for the discovery that plastics can, after certain modifications, be made electrically conductive.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] The work progressed to yield important practical applications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Conductive plastics can be used for anti-static substances for photographic film and 'smart' windows that can exclude light.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Semi-conductive polymers have been applied in light-emitting diodes, solar cells and displays in mobile telephones.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Future developments in molecular electronics are predicted to dramatically increase the speed while reducing the size of computers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid also travelled around the world for speaking engagements that impressed upon listeners the value of globalising the effort of innovation in the 21st century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] In one of his last courses, in 2001, MacDiarmid elected to lead a small seminar of incoming freshmen about his research activities.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Overall, his name is on over 600 published papers and 20 patents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Towards the end of his life, MacDiarmid was ill with myelodysplastic syndrome.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] In early February 2007 he was planning to travel back to New Zealand, when he fell down the stairs in his home in Drexel Hill, Pennsylvania, a suburb of Philadelphia, and died on 7 February 2007.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He is buried at Arlington Cemetery in Drexel Hill.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid's first wife, Marian Mathieu, who he had married in 1954, died in 1990.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] He is survived by four children: Heather McConnell, Dawn Hazelett, Duncan MacDiarmid and Gail Williams, from their marriage and nine grandchildren: Dr.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] Clayton Hazelett, Wesley Hazelett, Langston MacDiarmid, Aubree Williams, Austin Williams and George Williams.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid was also survived by his second wife, Gayl Gentile, whom he married in 2005; she died in 2014.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid was a first cousin of New Zealand expatriate painter Douglas MacDiarmid.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] The year after Alan received the Nobel Prize for Chemistry, Douglas painted a portrait Archived 11 November 2021 at the Wayback Machine of his cousin for the New Zealand Portrait Gallery.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alan-macdiarmid] MacDiarmid was also active as a naturist and nudist, and considered himself a sun-worshipper and keen waterskier.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The usual waveform of alternating current in most electric power circuits is a sine wave, whose positive half-period corresponds with positive direction of the current and vice versa (the full period is called a *cycle*).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] "Alternating current" most commonly refers to power distribution, but a wide range of other applications are technically alternating current although it is less common to describe them by that term.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In many applications, like guitar amplifiers, different waveforms are used, such as triangular waves or square waves.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] These types of alternating current carry information such as sound (audio) or images (video) sometimes carried by modulation of an AC carrier signal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] These currents typically alternate at higher frequencies than those used in power transmission.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Electrical energy is distributed as alternating current because AC voltage may be increased or decreased with a transformer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This allows the power to be transmitted through power lines efficiently at high voltage, which reduces the energy lost as heat due to resistance of the wire, and transformed to a lower, safer voltage for use.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Use of a higher voltage leads to significantly more efficient transmission of power.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This means that when transmitting a fixed power on a given wire, if the current is halved (by doubling the voltage), the power loss due to the wire's resistance will be reduced by a factor of four.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Consequently, power transmitted at a higher voltage requires less loss-producing current than for the same power at a lower voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Power is often transmitted at hundreds of kilovolts on pylons, and transformed down to tens of kilovolts to be transmitted on lower level lines, and finally transformed down to 100 V – 240 V for domestic use.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] High voltages have disadvantages, such as the increased insulation required, and generally increased difficulty in their safe handling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In a power plant, energy is generated at a convenient voltage for the design of a generator, and then stepped up to a high voltage for transmission.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Near the loads, the transmission voltage is stepped down to the voltages used by equipment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Consumer voltages vary somewhat depending on the country and size of load, but generally motors and lighting are built to use up to a few hundred volts between phases.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The voltage delivered to equipment such as lighting and motor loads is standardized, with an allowable range of voltage over which equipment is expected to operate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Standard power utilization voltages and percentage tolerance vary in the different mains power systems found in the world.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] High-voltage direct-current (HVDC) electric power transmission systems have become more viable as technology has provided efficient means of changing the voltage of DC power.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Transmission with high voltage direct current was not feasible in the early days of electric power transmission, as there was then no economically viable way to step the voltage of DC down for end user applications such as lighting incandescent bulbs.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Three-phase electrical generation is very common.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The simplest way is to use three separate coils in the generator stator, physically offset by an angle of 120° (one-third of a complete 360° phase) to each other.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Three current waveforms are produced that are equal in magnitude and 120° out of phase to each other.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] If coils are added opposite to these (60° spacing), they generate the same phases with reverse polarity and can be wired together.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In practice, higher *pole orders* are commonly used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For example, a 12-pole machine would have 36 coils (10° spacing).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The advantage is that lower rotational speeds can be used to generate the same frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For example, a 2-pole machine running at 3600 rpm and a 12-pole machine running at 600 rpm produce the same frequency; the lower speed is preferable for larger machines.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] If the load on a three-phase system is balanced equally among the phases, no current flows through the neutral point.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Even in the worst-case unbalanced (linear) load, the neutral current will not exceed the highest of the phase currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Non-linear loads (e.g. the switch-mode power supplies widely used) may require an oversized neutral bus and neutral conductor in the upstream distribution panel to handle harmonics.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Harmonics can cause neutral conductor current levels to exceed that of one or all phase conductors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For three-phase at utilization voltages a four-wire system is often used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] When stepping down three-phase, a transformer with a Delta (3-wire) primary and a Star (4-wire, center-earthed) secondary is often used so there is no need for a neutral on the supply side.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For smaller customers (just how small varies by country and age of the installation) only a single phase and neutral, or two phases and neutral, are taken to the property.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For larger installations, all three phases and neutral are taken to the main distribution panel.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] From the three-phase main panel, both single and three-phase circuits may lead off.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Three-wire single-phase systems, with a single center-tapped transformer giving two live conductors, is a common distribution scheme for residential and small commercial buildings in North America.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This arrangement is sometimes incorrectly referred to as *two phase*.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A similar method is used for a different reason on construction sites in the UK.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Small power tools and lighting are supposed to be supplied by a local center-tapped transformer with a voltage of 55 V between each power conductor and earth.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This significantly reduces the risk of electric shock in the event that one of the live conductors becomes exposed through an equipment fault whilst still allowing a reasonable voltage of 110 V between the two conductors for running the tools.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] An additional wire, called the bond (or earth) wire, is often connected between non-current-carrying metal enclosures and earth ground.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This conductor provides protection from electric shock due to accidental contact of circuit conductors with the metal chassis of portable appliances and tools.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Bonding all non-current-carrying metal parts into one complete system ensures there is always a low electrical impedance path to ground sufficient to carry any fault current for as long as it takes for the system to clear the fault.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This low impedance path allows the maximum amount of fault current, causing the overcurrent protection device (breakers, fuses) to trip or burn out as quickly as possible, bringing the electrical system to a safe state.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] All bond wires are bonded to ground at the main service panel, as is the neutral/identified conductor if present.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The frequency of the electrical system varies by country and sometimes within a country; most electric power is generated at either 50 or 60 Hz.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Some countries have a mixture of 50 Hz and 60 Hz supplies, notably electricity power transmission in Japan.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A low frequency eases the design of electric motors, particularly for hoisting, crushing and rolling applications, and commutator-type traction motors for applications such as railways.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] However, low frequency also causes noticeable flicker in arc lamps and incandescent light bulbs.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The use of lower frequencies also provided the advantage of lower transmission losses, which are proportional to frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls generators were built to produce 25 Hz power, as a compromise between low frequency for traction and heavy induction motors, while still allowing incandescent lighting to operate (although with noticeable flicker).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Most of the 25 Hz residential and commercial customers for Niagara Falls power were converted to 60 Hz by the late 1950s, although some 25 Hz industrial customers still existed as of the start of the 21st century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] 16.7 Hz power (formerly 16 2/3 Hz) is still used in some European rail systems, such as in Austria, Germany, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Off-shore, military, textile industry, marine, aircraft, and spacecraft applications sometimes use 400 Hz, for benefits of reduced weight of apparatus or higher motor speeds.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Computer mainframe systems were often powered by 400 Hz or 415 Hz for benefits of ripple reduction while using smaller internal AC to DC conversion units.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A direct current flows uniformly throughout the cross-section of a homogeneous electrically conducting wire.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] An alternating current of any frequency is forced away from the wire's center, toward its outer surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This is because an alternating current (which is the result of the acceleration of electric charge) creates electromagnetic waves (a phenomenon known as electromagnetic radiation).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The phenomenon of alternating current being pushed away from the center of the conductor is called skin effect, and a direct current does not exhibit this effect, since a direct current does not create electromagnetic waves.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] At very high frequencies, the current no longer flows *in* the wire, but effectively flows *on* the surface of the wire, within a thickness of a few skin depths.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The skin depth is the thickness at which the current density is reduced by 63%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Even at relatively low frequencies used for power transmission (50 Hz – 60 Hz), non-uniform distribution of current still occurs in sufficiently thick conductors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For example, the skin depth of a copper conductor is approximately 8.57 mm at 60 Hz, so high-current conductors are usually hollow to reduce their mass and cost.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This tendency of alternating current to flow predominantly in the periphery of conductors reduces the effective cross-section of the conductor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This increases the effective AC resistance of the conductor since resistance is inversely proportional to the cross-sectional area.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A conductor's AC resistance is higher than its DC resistance, causing a higher energy loss due to Ohmic heating (also called I2R loss).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For low to medium frequencies, conductors can be divided into stranded wires, each insulated from the others, with the relative positions of individual strands specially arranged within the conductor bundle.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Wire constructed using this technique is called Litz wire.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This measure helps to partially mitigate skin effect by forcing more equal current throughout the total cross section of the stranded conductors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] As written above, an alternating current is made of electric charge under periodic acceleration, which causes radiation of electromagnetic waves.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Depending on the frequency, different techniques are used to minimize the loss due to radiation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] At frequencies up to about 1 GHz, pairs of wires are twisted together in a cable, forming a twisted pair.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This reduces losses from electromagnetic radiation and inductive coupling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A twisted pair must be used with a balanced signaling system so that the two wires carry equal but opposite currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Each wire in a twisted pair radiates a signal, but it is effectively canceled by radiation from the other wire, resulting in almost no radiation loss.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables are commonly used at audio frequencies and above for convenience.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A coaxial cable has a conductive wire inside a conductive tube, separated by a dielectric layer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The current flowing on the surface of the inner conductor is equal and opposite to the current flowing on the inner surface of the outer tube.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The electromagnetic field is thus completely contained within the tube, and (ideally) no energy is lost to radiation or coupling outside the tube.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables have acceptably small losses for frequencies up to about 5 GHz.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For microwave frequencies greater than 5 GHz, the losses (due mainly to the dielectric separating the inner and outer tubes being a non-ideal insulator) become too large, making waveguides a more efficient medium for transmitting energy.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Coaxial cables often use a perforated dielectric layer to separate the inner and outer conductors in order to minimize the power dissipated by the dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Waveguides are similar to coaxial cables, as both consist of tubes, with the biggest difference being that waveguides have no inner conductor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Waveguides can have any arbitrary cross section, but rectangular cross sections are the most common.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Because waveguides do not have an inner conductor to carry a return current, waveguides cannot deliver energy by means of an electric current, but rather by means of a *guided* electromagnetic field.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Although surface currents do flow on the inner walls of the waveguides, those surface currents do not carry power.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Power is carried by the guided electromagnetic fields.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The surface currents are set up by the guided electromagnetic fields and have the effect of keeping the fields inside the waveguide and preventing leakage of the fields to the space outside the waveguide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Waveguides have dimensions comparable to the wavelength of the alternating current to be transmitted, so they are feasible only at microwave frequencies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In addition to this mechanical feasibility, electrical resistance of the non-ideal metals forming the walls of the waveguide causes dissipation of power (surface currents flowing on lossy conductors dissipate power).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] At higher frequencies, the power lost to this dissipation becomes unacceptably large.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] At frequencies greater than 200 GHz, waveguide dimensions become impractically small, and the ohmic losses in the waveguide walls become large.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Instead, fiber optics, which are a form of dielectric waveguides, can be used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For such frequencies, the concepts of voltages and currents are no longer used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Alternating currents are accompanied (or caused) by alternating voltages.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The peak-to-peak value of an AC voltage is defined as the difference between its positive peak and its negative peak.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Since the maximum value of $\sin(x)$ is +1 and the minimum value is −1, an AC voltage swings between $+V_{\text{peak}}$ and $-V_{\text{peak}}$ .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Below an AC waveform (with no DC component) is assumed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The RMS voltage is the square root of the mean over one cycle of the square of the instantaneous voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Rather than using instantaneous power, $p(t)$ , it is more practical to use a time-averaged power (where the averaging is performed over any integer number of cycles).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For this reason, AC power's waveform becomes Full-wave rectified sine, and its fundamental frequency is double that of the voltage's.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] To illustrate these concepts, consider a 230 V AC mains supply used in many countries around the world.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] It is so called because its root mean square value is 230 V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This means that the time-averaged power delivered $P_{\text{average}}$ is equivalent to the power delivered by a DC voltage of 230 V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] For 230 V AC, the peak voltage $V_{\text{peak}}$ is therefore $230{\text{ V}}\times {\sqrt {2}}$ , which is about 325 V, and the peak power $P_{\text{peak}}$ is $230\times R\times W\times 2$ , that is 460 RW.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] During the course of one cycle (two cycle as the power) the voltage rises from zero to 325 V, the power from zero to 460 RW, and both falls through zero.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Next, the voltage descends to reverse direction, −325 V, but the power ascends again to 460 RW, and both returns to zero.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Alternating current is used to transmit information, as in the cases of telephone and cable television.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Information signals are carried over a wide range of AC frequencies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] POTS telephone signals have a frequency of about 3 kHz, close to the baseband audio frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Cable television and other cable-transmitted information currents may alternate at frequencies of tens to thousands of megahertz.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] These frequencies are similar to the electromagnetic wave frequencies often used to transmit the same types of information over the air.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The first alternator to produce alternating current was an electric generator based on Michael Faraday's principles constructed by the French instrument maker Hippolyte Pixii in 1832.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Pixii later added a commutator to his device to produce the (then) more commonly used direct current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The earliest recorded practical application of alternating current is by Guillaume Duchenne, inventor and developer of electrotherapy.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1855, he announced that AC was superior to direct current for electrotherapeutic triggering of muscle contractions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Alternating current technology was developed further by the Hungarian Ganz Works company in the 1870s, and, in the 1880s, by Sebastian Ziani de Ferranti, Lucien Gaulard, and Galileo Ferraris.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1876, Russian engineer Pavel Yablochkov invented a lighting system where sets of induction coils were installed along a high-voltage AC line.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Instead of changing voltage, the primary windings transferred power to the secondary windings which were connected to one or several electric candles (arc lamps) of his own design, used to keep the failure of one lamp from disabling the entire circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1878, the Ganz factory, Budapest, Hungary, began manufacturing equipment for electric lighting and, by 1883, had installed over fifty systems in Austria-Hungary.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Their AC systems used arc and incandescent lamps, generators, and other equipment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The development of the alternating current transformer to change voltage from low to high level and back, allowed generation and consumption at low voltages and transmission, over great distances, at high voltage, with savings in the cost of conductors and energy losses.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A bipolar open-core power transformer developed by Lucien Gaulard and John Dixon Gibbs was demonstrated in London in 1881, and attracted the interest of Westinghouse.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] They exhibited an AC system powering arc and incandescent lights was installed along five railway stations for the Metropolitan Railway in London and a single-phase multiple-user AC distribution system Turin in 1884.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] These early induction coils with open magnetic circuits were inefficient at transferring power to loads.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Until about 1880, the paradigm for AC power transmission from a high voltage supply to a low voltage load was a series circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Open-core transformers with a ratio near 1:1 were connected with their primaries in series to allow use of a high voltage for transmission while presenting a low voltage to the lamps.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The inherent flaw in this method was that turning off a single lamp (or other electronic device) affected the voltage supplied to all others on the same circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Many adjustable transformer designs were introduced to compensate for this problematic characteristic of the series circuit, including those employing methods of adjusting the core or bypassing the magnetic flux around part of a coil.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The direct current systems did not have these drawbacks, giving it significant advantages over early AC systems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1890, he designed their power station at Deptford and converted the Grosvenor Gallery station across the Thames into an electrical substation, showing the way to integrate older plants into a universal AC supply system.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In the autumn of 1884, Károly Zipernowsky, Ottó Bláthy and Miksa Déri (ZBD), three engineers associated with the Ganz Works of Budapest, determined that open-core devices were impractical, as they were incapable of reliably regulating voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In both designs, the magnetic flux linking the primary and secondary windings traveled almost entirely within the confines of the iron core, with no intentional path through air (see toroidal cores).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The new transformers were 3.4 times more efficient than the open-core bipolar devices of Gaulard and Gibbs.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The Ganz factory in 1884 shipped the world's first five high-efficiency AC transformers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This first unit had been manufactured to the following specifications: 1,400 W, 40 Hz, 120:72 V, 11.6:19.4 A, ratio 1.67:1, one-phase, shell form.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] When employed in parallel connected electric distribution systems, closed-core transformers finally made it technically and economically feasible to provide electric power for lighting in homes, businesses and public spaces.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The other essential milestone was the introduction of 'voltage source, voltage intensive' (VSVI) systems' by the invention of constant voltage generators in 1885.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In early 1885, the three engineers also eliminated the problem of eddy current losses with the invention of the lamination of electromagnetic cores.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Ottó Bláthy also invented the first AC electricity meter.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In May 1885, at the Hungarian National Exhibition in Budapest, Deri, Blathy, and Zipernowski held a large-scale demonstration of what is widely regarded as the prototype of modern AC lighting systems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Their system used 75 transformers in parallel connection, supplying 1,067 incandescent Edison lamps from an AC generator that provided 1,350 V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The AC power system was developed and adopted rapidly after 1886.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] With this setup, the Westinghouse company successfully powered thirty 100-volt incandescent bulbs in twenty shops along the main street of Great Barrington.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] By the fall of that year Ganz engineers installed a ZBD transformer power system with AC generators in Rome.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Based on Stanley's success, the new Westinghouse Electric went on to develop alternating current (AC) electric infrastructure throughout the United States.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The spread of Westinghouse and other AC systems triggered a push back in late 1887 by Thomas Edison (a proponent of direct current), who attempted to discredit alternating current as too dangerous in a public campaign called the "war of the currents".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1888, alternating current systems gained further viability with the introduction of a functional AC motor, something these systems had lacked up till then.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The design, an induction motor, was independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla (with Tesla's design being licensed by Westinghouse in the US).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] This design was independently further developed into the modern practical three-phase form by Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky and Charles Eugene Lancelot Brown in Germany on one side, and Jonas Wenström in Sweden on the other, though Brown favored the two-phase system.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant, constructed in 1890, was among the first hydroelectric alternating current power plants.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A long-distance transmission of single-phase electricity from a hydroelectric generating plant in Oregon at Willamette Falls sent power fourteen miles downriver to downtown Portland for street lighting in 1890.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1891, another transmission system was installed in Telluride Colorado.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The first three-phase system was established in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The Tivoli–Rome transmission was completed in 1892.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The San Antonio Canyon Generator was the third commercial single-phase hydroelectric AC power plant in the United States to provide long-distance electricity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] It was completed on December 31, 1892, by Almarian William Decker to provide power to the city of Pomona, California, which was 14 miles away.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Meanwhile, the possibility of transferring electrical power from a waterfall at a distance was explored at the Grängesberg mine in Sweden.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] A 45 m fall at Hällsjön, Smedjebackens kommun, where a small iron work had been located, was selected.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1893, a three-phase 9.5 kv system was used to transfer 400 horsepower a distance of 15 km, becoming the first commercial application.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1893, Westinghouse built an alternating current system for the Chicago World Exposition.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] In 1893, Decker designed the first American commercial three-phase power plant using alternating current—the hydroelectric Mill Creek No.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] 1 Hydroelectric Plant near Redlands, California.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Decker's design incorporated 10 kV three-phase transmission and established the standards for the complete system of generation, transmission and motors used in USA today.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The original Niagara Falls Adams Power Plant with three two-phase generators was put into operation in August 1895, but was connected to the remote transmission system only in 1896.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] The Jaruga Hydroelectric Power Plant in Croatia was set in operation two days later, on 28 August 1895.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Its generator (42 Hz, 240 kW) was made and installed by the Hungarian company Ganz, while the transmission line from the power plant to the City of Šibenik was 11.5 kilometers (7.1 mi) long, and the municipal distribution grid 3000 V/110 V included six transforming stations.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Alternating current circuit theory developed rapidly in the latter part of the 19th and early 20th century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Notable contributors to the theoretical basis of alternating current calculations include Charles Steinmetz, Oliver Heaviside, and many others.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/alternating-current] Calculations in unbalanced three-phase systems were simplified by the symmetrical components methods discussed by Charles LeGeyt Fortescue in 1918.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte are the most inexpensive type and also those with widest range of sizes, capacitance and voltage values.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They are made with capacitance values from 0.1 μF up to 2,700,000 μF (2.7 F), and voltage ratings ranging from 4 V up to 630 V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The liquid electrolyte provides oxygen for re-forming or "self-healing" of the dielectric oxide layer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] However, it can evaporate through a temperature-dependent drying-out process, which causes electrical parameters to drift, limiting the service life time of the capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Due to their relatively high capacitance values aluminum electrolytic capacitors have low impedance values even at lower frequencies like mains frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Special types are used for energy storage, for example in photoflash or strobe applications or for signal coupling in audio applications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminium electrolytic capacitors are polarized capacitors because of their anodization principle.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They can only be operated with DC voltage applied with the correct polarity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Operating the capacitor with the wrong polarity, or with AC voltage, leads to a short circuit which can destroy the component.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The exception is the bipolar or non-polar aluminum electrolytic capacitor, which has a back-to-back configuration of two anodes in a single case, and which can be safely used in AC applications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors use a chemical feature of some special metals, earlier called "valve metals".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Applying a positive voltage to the anode material in an electrolytic bath forms an insulating oxide layer with a thickness corresponding to the applied voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This oxide layer acts as the dielectric in an electrolytic capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] After forming a dielectric oxide on the rough anode structures, a counter-electrode has to match the rough insulating oxide surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This is provided by the electrolyte, which acts as the cathode electrode of an electrolytic capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytes may be "non-solid" (wet, liquid) or "solid".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Non-solid electrolytes, as a liquid medium that has an *ion conductivity* caused by moving ions, are relatively insensitive to voltage spikes or current surges.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Solid electrolytes have an *electron conductivity*, which makes solid electrolytic capacitors sensitive to voltages spikes or current surges.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The anodic generated insulating oxide layer is destroyed if the polarity of the applied voltage changes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Every electrolytic capacitor in principle forms a "plate capacitor" whose capacitance is greater the larger the electrode area A and the permittivity ε, and the thinner the thickness (d) of the dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The capacitance is proportional to the product of the area of one plate multiplied with the permittivity, divided by the thickness of the dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors obtain their large capacitance values by a large area and small dielectric thickness.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The dielectric thickness of electrolytic capacitors is very thin, in the range of nanometers per volt, but the voltage strengths of these oxide layers are quite high.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] All etched or sintered anodes have a much higher surface compared to a smooth surface of the same area.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This increases the capacitance value by a factor of up to 200 for aluminum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] An aluminum electrolytic capacitor with a non-solid electrolyte always consists of two aluminum foils separated mechanically by a spacer, mostly paper, which is saturated with a liquid or gel-like electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] One of the aluminum foils, the anode, is etched (roughened) to increase the surface and oxidized (formed).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The second aluminum foil, called the "cathode foil", serves to make electrical contact with the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] A paper spacer mechanically separates the foils to avoid direct metallic contact.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Both foils and the spacer are wound and the winding is impregnated with liquid electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The electrolyte, which serves as cathode of the capacitor, covers the etched rough structure of the oxide layer on the anode perfectly and makes the increased anode surface effectual.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] After impregnation the impregnated winding is mounted in an aluminum case and sealed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] By design, a non-solid aluminum electrolytic capacitor has a second aluminum foil, the so-called cathode foil, for contacting the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This structure of an aluminum electrolytic capacitor results in a characteristic result because the second aluminum (cathode) foil is also covered with an insulating oxide layer naturally formed by air.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Therefore, the construction of the electrolytic capacitor consists of two single series-connected capacitors with capacitance CA of the anode and capacitance CK of the cathode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] It follows that the total capacitance of the capacitor Ce-cap is mainly determined by the anode capacitance CA when the cathode capacitance CK is very large compared with the anode capacitance CA.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This requirement is given when the cathode capacitance CK is approximately 10 times higher than the anode capacitance CA.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This can be easily achieved because the natural oxide layer on a cathode surface has a voltage proof of approximately 1.5 V and is therefore very thin.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Although the present article only refers in essence to aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte, an overview of the different types of aluminum electrolytic capacitors is given here in order to highlight the differences.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors are divided into two sub-types depending on whether they make use of liquid or solid electrolyte systems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Because the different electrolyte systems can be constructed with a variety of different materials, they include further sub-types.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The following table shows an overview over the main characteristics of the different types of aluminum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte are the best known and most widely used electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] These components can be found on almost all boards of electronic equipment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They are characterized by particularly inexpensive and easy to process base materials.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminum capacitors with liquid electrolytes based on borax or organic solvents have a large range of types and ratings.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Capacitors with water-based electrolytes are often found in digital devices for mass production.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Types with solid manganese dioxide electrolyte have served in the past as a "tantalum replacement".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Polymer aluminum electrolytic capacitors with solid conductive polymer electrolytes are becoming increasingly important, especially in devices with a flat design, such as tablet PCs and flat panel displays.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors with hybrid electrolytes are relatively new on the market.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] With their hybrid electrolyte system, they combine the improved conductivity of the polymer with the advantage of liquid electrolytes for better self-healing properties of the oxide layer, so that the capacitors have the advantages of both low ESR and low leakage current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The basic material of the anode for aluminum electrolytic capacitors is a foil with a thickness of ~ 20–100 μm made of aluminum with a high purity of at least 99.99%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This is etched (roughened) in an electrochemical process to increase the effective electrode surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] By etching the surface of the anode, depending on the required rated voltage, the surface area can be increased by a factor of approximately 200 with respect to a smooth surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] After etching the aluminum anode the roughed surface is "anodic oxidized" or "formed".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] An electrically insulating oxide layer Al2O3 is thereby formed on the aluminum surface by application of a current in correct polarity if it is inserted in an electrolytic bath.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This oxide layer is the capacitor dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This process of oxide formation is carried out in two reaction steps whereby the oxygen for this reaction has to come from the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This reaction is accelerated by a high electric field and high temperatures, and is accompanied by a pressure buildup in the capacitor housing caused by the released hydrogen gas.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The aluminum oxide serves as dielectric and also protects the metallic aluminum against aggressive chemical reactions from the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] However, the converted layer of aluminum oxide is usually not homogeneous.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] It forms a complex multilayer structured laminate of amorphous, crystalline and porous crystalline aluminum oxide mostly covered with small residual parts of unconverted aluminum hydroxide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For this reason, in the formation of the anode foil, the oxide film is structured by a special chemical treatment so that either an amorphous oxide or a crystalline oxide is formed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The amorphous oxide variety yields higher mechanical and physical stability and fewer defects, thus increasing the long term stability and lowering the leakage current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Amorphous oxide has a dielectric ratio of ~ 1.4 nm/V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Compared to crystalline aluminum oxide, which has a dielectric ratio of ~1.0 nm/V, the amorphous variety has a 40% lower capacitance at the same anode surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The disadvantage of crystalline oxide is its greater sensitivity to tensile stress, which may lead to microcracks when subjected to mechanical (winding) or thermal (soldering) stressors during the post-forming processes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The various properties of oxide structures affect the subsequent characteristics of the electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Anode foils with amorphous oxide are primarily used for electrolytic capacitors with stable long-life characteristics, for capacitors with low leakage current values, and for e-caps with rated voltages up to about 100 volts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Capacitors with higher voltages, for example photoflash capacitors, usually containing anode foils with crystalline oxide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Because the thickness of the effective dielectric is proportional to the forming voltage, the dielectric thickness can be tailored to the rated voltage of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For example, for low voltage types a 10 V electrolytic capacitor has a dielectric thickness of only about 0.014 μm, a 100 V electrolytic capacitor of only about 0.14 μm.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Thus, the dielectric strength also influences the size of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] However, due to standardized safety margins the actual forming voltage of electrolytic capacitors is higher than the rated voltage of the component.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Aluminum anode foils are manufactured as so-called "mother rolls" of about 500 mm in width.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They are pre-formed for the desired rated voltage and with the desired oxide layer structure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] To produce the capacitors, the anode widths and lengths, as required for a capacitor, have to be cut from the mother roll.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The second aluminum foil in the electrolytic capacitor, called the "cathode foil", serves to make electrical contact with the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This foil has a somewhat lower degree of purity, about 99.8%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] It is always provided with a very thin oxide layer, which arises from the contact of the aluminum surface with the air in a natural way.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In order to reduce the contact resistance to the electrolyte and to make it difficult for oxide formation during discharging, the cathode foil is alloyed with metals such as copper, silicon, or titanium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The cathode foil is also etched to enlarge the surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Because of the extremely thin oxide layer, which corresponds to a voltage proof of about 1.5 V, their specific capacitance is, however, much higher than that of anode foils.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] To justify the need for a large surface capacitance of the cathode foil see the section on charge/discharge stability below.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The cathode foils, as the anode foils, are manufactured as so-called "mother rolls", from which widths and lengths are cut off, as required, for capacitor production.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The electrolytic capacitor got its name from the electrolyte, the conductive liquid inside the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] As a liquid it can be adapted to the porous structure of the anode and the grown oxide layer with the same shape and form as a "tailor-made" cathode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] An electrolyte always consists of a mixture of solvents and additives to meet given requirements.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The main electrical property of the electrolyte is its conductivity, which is physically an ion-conductivity in liquids.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In addition to the good conductivity of operating electrolytes, various other requirements are, among other things, chemical stability, high flash point, chemical compatibility with aluminum, low viscosity, minimal negative environmental impact and low cost.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The electrolyte should also provide oxygen for forming and self-healing processes, and all this within a temperature range as wide as possible.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This diversity of requirements for the liquid electrolyte results in a wide variety of proprietary solutions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The anode and cathode foils must be protected from direct contact with each other because such contact, even at relatively low voltages, may lead to a short circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In case of direct contact of both foils the oxide layer on the anode surface gives no protection.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] A spacer or separator made of a special highly absorbent paper with high purity protects the two metal foils from direct contact.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This capacitor paper also serves as a reservoir for the electrolyte to extend the lifetime of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The thickness of the spacer depends on the rated voltage of the electrolytic capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For higher voltages, several layers of paper (duplex paper) are used to increase the breakdown strength.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The encapsulation of aluminum electrolytic capacitors is also made of aluminum in order to avoid galvanic reactions, normally with an aluminum case (can, tub).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For radial electrolytic capacitors it is connected across the electrolyte with a non-defined resistance to the cathode (ground).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For axial electrolytic capacitors, however, the housing is specifically designed with a direct contact to the cathode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In case of a malfunction, overload or wrong polarity operating inside the electrolytic capacitor housing, substantial gas pressure can arise.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The tubs are designed to open a pressure relief vent and release high pressure gas, including parts of the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This vent protects against bursting, explosion or fly away of the metal tub.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For smaller housings the pressure relief vent is carved in the bottom or the notch of the tub.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Larger capacitors like screw-terminal capacitors have a lockable overpressure vent and must be mounted in an upright position.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The sealing materials of aluminum electrolytic capacitors depend on the different styles.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For larger screw-terminal and snap-in capacitors the sealing washer is made of a plastic material.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Axial electrolytic capacitors usually have a sealing washer made of phenolic resin laminated with a layer of rubber.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Radial electrolytic capacitors use a rubber plug with a very dense structure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] All sealing materials must be inert to the chemical parts of the electrolyte and may not contain soluble compounds that could lead to contamination of the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] To avoid leakage, the electrolyte must not be aggressive to the sealing material.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The production process starts with mother rolls.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] First, the etched, roughened and pre-formed anode foil on the mother roll as well as the spacer paper and the cathode foil are cut to the required width.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The foils are fed to an automatic winder, which makes a wound section in a consecutive operation involving three sequential steps: terminal welding, winding, and length cutting.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In the next production step the wound section fixed at the lead out terminals is soaked with electrolyte under vacuum impregnation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The impregnated winding is then built into an aluminum case, provided with a rubber sealing disc, and mechanically tightly sealed by curling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Thereafter, the capacitor is provided with an insulating shrink sleeve film.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This optically ready capacitor is then contacted at rated voltage in a high temperature post-forming device for healing all the dielectric defects resulting from the cutting and winding procedure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] After post-forming, a 100% final measurement of capacitance, leakage current, and impedance takes place.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Taping closes the manufacturing process; the capacitors are ready for delivery.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In 1875, French researcher Eugène Ducretet discovered that certain "valve metals" (aluminum and others) can form an oxide layer that blocks an electric current from flowing in one direction but allows it to flow in the reverse direction.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Karol Pollak, a producer of accumulators, found out that the oxide layer on an aluminum anode remained stable in a neutral or alkaline electrolyte, even when the power was switched off.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In 1896 he obtained a patent for an *Electric liquid capacitor with aluminum electrodes* (de: *Elektrischer Flüssigkeitskondensator mit Aluminiumelektroden*) based on the idea of using the oxide layer in a polarized capacitor in combination with a neutral or slightly alkaline electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The first electrolytic capacitors realized industrially consisted of a metallic box used as cathode, filled with a borax electrolyte dissolved in water, in which a folded aluminum anode plate was inserted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Applying a DC voltage from outside, an oxide layer was formed on the surface of the anode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The advantage of these capacitors was that they were significantly smaller and cheaper than all other capacitors at this time with respect to realized capacitance value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This construction with different styles of anode construction but with a case as cathode and a container as the electrolyte was used up to the 1930s and was called a "wet" electrolytic capacitor, referring to its high water content.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The first common application of wet aluminum electrolytic capacitors was in large telephone exchanges, to reduce relay hash (noise) on the 48 volt DC power supply.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The development of AC-operated domestic radio receivers in the late 1920s created a demand for large-capacitance (for the time) and high-voltage capacitors for the valve amplifier technique, typically at least 4 microfarads and rated at around 500 volts DC.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Waxed paper and oiled silk film capacitors were available, but devices with that order of capacitance and voltage rating were bulky and prohibitively expensive.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The ancestor of the modern electrolytic capacitor was patented by Samuel Ruben in 1925, who teamed with Philip Mallory, the founder of the battery company that is now known as Duracell International.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Ruben's idea adopted the stacked construction of a silver mica capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] He introduced a separate second foil to contact the electrolyte adjacent the anode foil instead of using the electrolyte-filled container as the cathode of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The stacked second foil got its own terminal additional to the anode terminal and the container had no longer an electrical function.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This type of electrolytic capacitor with one anode foil separated from a cathode foil by a liquid or gel-like electrolyte of a non-aqueous nature, which is therefore dry in the sense of having a very low water content, became known as the "dry" type of electrolytic capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This invention, together with the invention of wound foils separated with a paper spacer 1927 by A.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Eckel, Hydra-Werke (Germany), reduced the size and the price significantly, which helped make the new radios affordable for a broader group of customers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] William Dubilier, whose first patent for electrolytic capacitors was filed in 1928, industrialized the new ideas for electrolytic capacitors and started large-scale commercial production in 1931 in the Cornell-Dubilier (CD) factory in Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] At the same time in Berlin, Germany, the "Hydra-Werke", an AEG company, started the production of electrolytic capacitors in large quantities.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Already in his patent application of 1886, Pollak wrote that the capacitance of the capacitor increased if the surface of the anode foil was roughened.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] A number of methods have since been developed for roughening the anode surface, mechanical methods like sand blasting or scratching, and chemical etching with acids and acid salts forced by high currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Some of these methods were developed in the CD factory between 1931 and 1938.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Today (2014), electro-chemically etching of low voltage foils can achieve up to a 200 fold increase in surface area compared to a smooth surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Progress relating to the etching process is the reason for the ongoing reduction in the dimensions of aluminum electrolytic capacitors over the past decades.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The period after World War II is associated with a rapid development in radio and television technology as well as in industrial applications, which had great influence on production quantities but also on styles, sizes and series diversification of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] New electrolytes based on organic liquids reduced leakage currents and ESR, broadened temperature ranges and increased lifetimes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Corrosion phenomena caused by chlorine and water could be avoided by a higher purity manufacturing processes and by using additives in the electrolytes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The development of tantalum electrolytic capacitors in the early 1950s with manganese dioxide as solid electrolyte, which has a 10 times better conductivity than all other types of non-solid electrolytes, also influenced the development of aluminum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In 1964 the first aluminum electrolytic capacitors with solid electrolyte (Solid aluminum capacitor (SAL)) appeared on the market, developed by Philips.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The great diversity of the many series of aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes up to now (2014) is an indicator of the adaptability of the capacitors to meet different industrial requirements.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In 1983 a further reduction of the ESR was achieved by Sanyo with its "OS-CON" aluminum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] These capacitors use as solid organic conductor the charge transfer salt TTF-TCNQ (tetracyanoquinodimethane), which provided an improvement in conductivity by a factor of 10 with respect to the manganese dioxide electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The ESR values of TCNQ-capacitors were significantly reduced by the discovery of conducting polymers by Alan J.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Heeger, Alan MacDiarmid and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The conductivity of conductive polymers such as polypyrrole [14] or PEDOT are better than that of TCNQ by a factor of 100 to 500, and are close to the conductivity of metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In 1991 Panasonic put its "SP-Cap", a polymer aluminum electrolytic capacitor, on the market.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] These electrolytic capacitors with polymer electrolytes achieved ESR values low enough to compete with ceramic multilayer capacitors (MLCCs).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They were still less expensive than tantalum capacitors and were a short time later used in devices with a flat design, such as laptops and cell phones.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] New water-based electrolytes were developed in Japan from the mid-1980s with the goal of reducing ESR for inexpensive non-solid electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Water is inexpensive, an effective solvent for electrolytes, and significantly improves the conductivity of the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Japanese manufacturer Rubycon was a leader in the development of new water-based electrolyte systems with enhanced conductivity in the late 1990s.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The new series of non-solid capacitors with water-based electrolyte was called in the data sheets "Low-ESR", "Low-Impedance", "Ultra-Low-Impedance" or "High-Ripple Current" series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] From 2000 to 2005, a stolen recipe of such a water-based electrolyte missing important stabilizing substances led to the problem of mass-bursting capacitors in computers and power supplies, which became known as the "Capacitor Plague".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In these capacitors the water reacts quite aggressively and even violently with aluminum, accompanied by strong heat and gas development in the capacitor, and often leads to the explosion of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The electrical characteristics of capacitors are harmonized by the international generic specification IEC 60384-1.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The basic unit of electrolytic capacitors capacitance is the microfarad (μF, or less correctly uF).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The capacitance value specified in manufacturers' data sheets is called the rated capacitance CR or nominal capacitance CN and is the value for which the capacitor has been designed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Standardized measuring conditions for electrolytic capacitors are an AC measurement with 0.5 V at a frequency of 100/120 Hz and a temperature of 20 °C.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The capacitance value of an electrolytic capacitor depends on the measuring frequency and temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The value at a measuring frequency of 1 kHz is about 10% less than the 100/120 Hz value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Therefore, the capacitance values of electrolytic capacitors are not directly comparable and differ from those of film capacitors or ceramic capacitors, whose capacitance is measured at 1 kHz or higher.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Measured with an AC measuring method with 100/120 Hz the measured capacitance value is the closest value to the electrical charge stored in the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The stored charge is measured with a special discharge method and is called DC capacitance.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The DC capacitance is about 10% higher than the 100/120 Hz AC capacitance.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The DC capacitance is of interest for discharge applications like photoflash.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The percentage of allowed deviation of the measured capacitance from the rated value is called capacitance tolerance.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors are available in different tolerance series, whose values are specified in the E series specified in IEC 60063.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For abbreviated marking in tight spaces, a letter code for each tolerance is specified in IEC 60062.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The required capacitance tolerance is determined by the particular application.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors that are often used for filtering and bypassing capacitors do not need narrow tolerances because they are not used for accurate frequency applications, such as for oscillators.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In IEC 60384-1 the allowed operating voltage is called the "rated voltage" UR or the "nominal voltage" UN.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The rated voltage is the maximum DC voltage or peak pulse voltage that may be applied continuously at any temperature within the rated temperature range.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The voltage proof of electrolytic capacitors, which is directly proportional to the dielectric layer thickness, decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For some applications it is important to use a high temperature range.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Lowering the voltage applied at a higher temperature maintains safety margins.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For some capacitor types, therefore, the IEC standard specifies a second "temperature derated voltage" for a higher temperature range, the "category voltage" UC.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The category voltage is the maximum DC voltage, peak pulse voltage or superimposed AC voltage that may be applied continuously to a capacitor at any temperature within the category temperature range.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors can be applied for a short time with an overvoltage, also called a surge voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Usually, for capacitors with a rated voltage of ≤ 315 volts, the surge voltage is 1.15 times the rated voltage and for capacitors with a rated voltage exceeding 315 volts the surge voltage is 1.10 times the rated voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte are relatively insensitive to high and short-term transient voltages higher than the surge voltage, if the frequency and the energy content of the transients is low.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This ability depends on the rated voltage and component size.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Low energy transient voltages lead to a voltage limitation similar to a zener diode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The electrochemical oxide forming processes take place when voltage in correct polarity is applied and generates an additional oxide when transients arise.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This formation is accompanied with heat and hydrogen gas generation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This is tolerable if the energy content of the transient is low.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] However, when a transient peak voltage causes an electric field strength that is too high for the dielectric, it can directly cause a short circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] An unambiguous and general specification of tolerable transients or peak voltages is not possible.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In every case transients arise, the application has to be carefully approved.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors with solid electrolyte cannot withstand transients or peak voltages higher than the surge voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Transients for this type of electrolytic capacitor may destroy the component.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors are polarized capacitors and generally require an anode electrode voltage to be positive relative to the cathode voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] However, the cathode foil of aluminum electrolytic capacitors is provided with a very thin, natural air-originated oxide layer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This oxide layer has a voltage proof of approximately 1 to 1.5 V.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Therefore, aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte can continuously withstand a very small reverse voltage and, for example, can be measured with an AC voltage of about 0.5 V, as specified in relevant standards.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] At a reverse voltage lower than −1.5 V at room temperature, the cathode aluminum foil begins to build up an oxide layer corresponding to the applied voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This is aligned with generating hydrogen gas with increasing pressure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] At the same time the oxide layer on the anode foil begins dissolution of the oxide, which weakens the voltage proof.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It is now a question of the outside circuit whether the increasing gas pressure from oxidization leads to bursting of the case, or the weakened anode oxide leads to a breakdown with a short circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If the outside circuit is high-ohmic the capacitor fails and the vent opens due to high gas pressure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If the outside circuit is low-ohmic, an internal short-circuit is more likely.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In every case a reverse voltage lower than −1.5 V at room temperature may cause the component to catastrophically fail due to a dielectric breakdown or overpressure, which causes the capacitor to burst, often in a spectacularly dramatic fashion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Modern electrolytic capacitors have a safety vent that is typically either a scored section of the case or a specially designed end seal to vent the hot gas/liquid, but ruptures can still be dramatic.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] To minimize the likelihood of a polarized electrolytic being incorrectly inserted into a circuit, the polarity is very clearly indicated on the case, see the section headed "Polarity marking".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Special bipolar capacitors designed for AC operation, usually referred to as "bipolar", "non-polarized" or "NP" types, are available.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In these, the capacitors have two anode foils of opposite polarity connected in series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] On each of the alternate halves of the AC cycle, one anode acts as a blocking dielectric, preventing reverse voltage from damaging the opposite anode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In general, a capacitor is seen as a storage component for electric energy.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] But this is only one capacitor function.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] A capacitor can also act as an AC resistor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Especially aluminum electrolytic capacitors are used in many applications as a decoupling capacitors to filter or bypass undesired biased AC frequencies to the ground or for capacitive coupling of audio AC signals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Then the dielectric is used only for blocking DC.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For such applications the AC resistance, the impedance is as important as the capacitance value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The impedance is the vector sum of reactance and resistance; it describes the phase difference and the ratio of amplitudes between sinusoidally varying voltage and sinusoidally varying current at a given frequency in an AC circuit.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In other words, impedance is a frequency-dependent AC resistance and possesses both magnitude and phase at a particular frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In capacitor data sheets, only the impedance magnitude |Z| is specified, and simply written as "Z".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In this sense the impedance is a measure of the capacitor's ability to pass alternating currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Impedance can be calculated using the idealized components of a capacitor's series-equivalent circuit, including an ideal capacitor $\scriptstyle C$ , a resistor $\scriptstyle ESR$ , and an inductance $\scriptstyle ESL$ .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In the special case of resonance, in which the both reactive resistances $\scriptstyle X_{C}$ and $\scriptstyle X_{L}$ have the same value ( $\scriptstyle X_{C}=X_{L}$ ), then the impedance is only determined by $\scriptstyle ESR$ .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The impedance specified in the data sheets of various capacitors often shows typical curves for different capacitance values.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The impedance at the resonant frequency defines the best working point for coupling or decoupling circuits.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The higher the capacitance the lower the operable frequency range.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Due to their large capacitance values, aluminum electrolytic capacitors have relatively good decoupling properties in the lower frequency range up to about 1 MHz or a little more.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This and the relatively low price is often the reason for using electrolytic capacitors in 50/60 Hz standard or switched-mode power supplies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The equivalent series resistance (ESR) summarizes all resistive losses of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] These are the terminal resistances, the contact resistance of the electrode contact, the line resistance of the electrodes, the electrolyte resistance, and the dielectric losses in the dielectric oxide layer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] ESR depends on temperature and frequency.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte the ESR generally decreases with increasing frequency and temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] ESR influences the remaining superimposed AC ripple behind smoothing and may influence circuit functionality.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Related to the capacitor, ESR is accountable for internal heat generation if a ripple current flows over the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This internal heat reduces capacitor lifetime.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Referring to the IEC/EN 60384-1 standard, the impedance values of electrolytic capacitors are measured at 10 kHz or 100 kHz, depending on the capacitance and voltage of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For aluminum electrolytic capacitors, for historical reasons sometimes the dissipation factor tan δ is specified in the relevant data sheets instead of the $\scriptstyle ESR$ .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The dissipation factor is determined by the tangent of the phase angle between the capacitive reactance $\scriptstyle X_{C}$ minus the inductive reactance $\scriptstyle X_{L}$ and the $\scriptstyle ESR$ .
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] A ripple current is the RMS value of a superimposed AC current of any frequency and any waveform of the current curve for continuous operation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It arises, for example, in power supplies (including switched-mode power supplies) after rectifying an AC voltage and flows as biased charge and discharge current through the decoupling or smoothing capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] which result in heat generation inside the capacitor winding core.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This internally generated heat, together with ambient temperature and possibly other external heat sources, leads to a capacitor core temperature whose hottest area is located in the winding, having a temperature difference of *Δ T* compared with the ambient temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This heat has to be distributed as thermal losses *PV th* over the capacitor's surface *A* and the thermal resistance *β* to the ambient environment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The thermal resistance β depends on the case size of the relevant capacitor and if applicable on additional cooling conditions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If the internally generated power losses *PV el* dissipated by thermal radiation, convection, and thermal conduction to the ambient environment correspond to the thermal losses *PV th,*, then a temperature balance between capacitor temperature and ambient temperature is given.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Typically, the specified rated value for maximum ripple current in manufacturers' data sheets is calculated for a heating the capacitor core (cell) of 10 °C for 85 °C series, 5 °C for 105 °C series and 3 °C for 125 °C series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The rated ripple current of aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte corresponds with the specified lifetime of the capacitor series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This current may flow permanent over the capacitor up to the maximum temperature during the specified or calculated time.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Ripple current lower than specified or forced cooling lengthen the capacitor's lifetime.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The lifetime of electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte depends on the evaporation rate and therefore on the core temperature of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] With forced cooling or special positioning of the capacitor on the PCB the lifetime can be influenced positively.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The ripple current is specified as an effective (RMS) value at 100 or 120 Hz or at 10 kHz at upper category temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Non-sinusoidal ripple currents have to be analyzed and separated into their single sinusoidal frequencies by means of Fourier analysis and summarized by squared addition of the single currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Periodically appearing high current pulses, which may be much higher than the rated ripple current, have to be analyzed in the same matter.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Because the ESR decreases with increasing frequencies. the ripple current data sheet value, specified at 100/120 Hz, can be higher at higher frequencies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In cases like this manufacturers specify correction factors for ripple current values at higher frequencies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For example, the ripple current at 10 kHz can usually be approximated to be 30 to 40% higher than the 100/120 value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If the ripple current exceeds the rated value, the corresponding heat generation exceeds the capacitor's temperature limit and may destroy the internal structure (voltage proof, boiling point) of the capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Then the components tend to short circuiting, vent opening or explosion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Ripple currents higher than rated values are possible only with forced cooling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes always contain, in addition to the anode foil, a cathode foil that serves as electrical contact to the electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This cathode foil is provided with a very thin, natural, air-originated oxide layer, which act also as a dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Thus, the capacitor construction forms a series circuit of two capacitors, the capacitance of the anode foil CA and the cathode foil CK.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] As described above, the capacitance of the capacitor Ce-cap is mainly determined by the anode capacitance CA when the cathode capacitance CK is approximately 10 times higher than the anode capacitance CA.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes normally can be charged up to the rated voltage without any current limitation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This property is a result of the limited ion movability in the liquid electrolyte, which slows down the voltage ramp across the dielectric, and the capacitor's ESR.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] During discharging the internal construction of the capacitor reverses the internal polarity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The cathode (-) gets an anode (+), and changes the current flow direction.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Two voltages arise over these electrode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In principle the voltage distribution over both electrodes behaves as the reciprocally CV product of each electrode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The design rule of high cathode capacitance assures that the voltage appearing over the cathode during discharge is not higher than roughly 1.5 V, that is its natural air-originated voltage proof.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] No further post-forming of the cathode foil takes place, which may lead to capacitance degradation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Then the capacitors are discharge-proof.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Small (diameter <25 mm) aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes can normally be charged up to the rated voltage without any current surge, peak or pulse limitation up to a peak current value of about 50 A.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Only the frequency of peaks integrated over time must not exceed the maximal specified ripple current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] A characteristic property of electrolytic capacitors is the "leakage current".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This DC current is represented by the resistor Rleak in parallel with the capacitor in the series-equivalent circuit of electrolytic capacitors, and flows if a voltage is applied.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current includes all weak imperfections of the dielectric caused by unwanted chemical processes and mechanical damage and is the DC current that can pass through the dielectric after applying a voltage in correct polarity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It depends on the capacitance value, on applied voltage and temperature of the capacitor, on measuring time, on the kind of electrolyte, and on preconditions like previous storage time without voltage applied or thermic stress from soldering.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] (All non-solid electrolytic capacitors needs a recovery time of some hours after soldering before measuring the leakage current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Non-solid chip capacitors need a recovery time after reflow soldering of about 24 hours.) Leakage current is reduced by applying operational voltage by self-healing processes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current drops in the first minutes after applying DC voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In this time the dielectric oxide layer can repair all weaknesses by building up new layers in a self-healing process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The time it takes leakage current to drop generally depends on the kind of electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Solid electrolytes' leakage current drops much faster than in the case of non-solid types, but it remain at a somewhat higher level.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Wet electrolytic capacitors with high water content electrolytes in the first minutes generally have higher leakage current than those with organic electrolyte, but after several minutes they reach the same level.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Although the leakage current of electrolytic capacitors is higher compared with the current flow over the insulation resistance at ceramic or film capacitors, the self-discharge of modern non-solid electrolytic capacitors can take several weeks.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current *Ileak* specification in manufacturers' data sheets refers to the capacitor's capacitance value *CR,* rated voltage *UR,* a correlation factor and a minimum current value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] After a measuring time of 2 or 5 minutes, depending on the data sheet specification, the measured leakage current value has to be lower than the calculated value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Normally the leakage current is always lower the longer the capacitor voltage is applied.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current during operation after, for example, one hour is the operational leakage current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This value depends strongly on the manufacturer's series characteristics.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It could be lower than 1/100 of the specified value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current depends on the applied voltage and the ambient temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The value during continuous operation at 85 °C is approximately four times higher than at 20 °C.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Otherwise the value is approximately one half, reducing the applied voltage to 70% of the rated voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Non-solid aluminum electrolytic capacitors that leakage current after an operation time of, for example, one hour remain on a higher level than specified.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Mostly they have been mechanically damaged internally due to high mechanical stress during mounting.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Dielectric absorption occurs when a capacitor that has remained charged for a long time discharges only incompletely when briefly discharged.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Although an ideal capacitor would reach zero volts after discharge, real capacitors develop a small voltage from time-delayed dipole discharging, a phenomenon that is also called dielectric relaxation, "soakage" or "battery action".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Dielectric absorption may be a problem in circuits using very small currents in electronic circuits, such as long-time-constant integrators or sample-and-hold circuits.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Dielectric absorption is not a problem in most applications of electrolytic capacitors supporting power supply lines.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] But especially for electrolytic capacitors with high rated voltage the voltage at the terminals generated by the dielectric absorption can be a safety risk to personnel or circuits.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In order to prevent shocks most very large capacitors are shipped with shorting wires that need to be removed before use.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The reliability prediction of aluminum electrolytic capacitors is generally expressed as a Failure rate λ, abbreviated FIT (Failures In Time).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It is a measure of the number of failures per unit hour during the time of constant random failures in the bathtub curve.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The flat part in the bathtub curve corresponds with the calculated lifetime or service life of non-solid electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The failure rate is used to calculate a survival probability for a desired lifetime of an electronic circuit in combination with other participating components.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] FIT is the number of failures that can be expected in one billion (109) component-hours of operation at fixed working conditions (e.g., 1000 components for 1 million hours, or 1 million components for 1000 hours) (1 ppm/1000 hours) each during the period of constant random failures.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This failure rate model implicitly assumes the idea of "random failure".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Individual components fail at random times but at a predictable rate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Failures are short circuits, open circuits and degradation failures (exceeding specified limits of electrical parameters).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The reciprocal value of FIT is the MTBF, the Mean Time Between Failures.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The standard operating conditions for the failure rate FIT are 40 °C and 0.5 UR.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For other conditions of applied voltage, current load, temperature, capacitance value, circuit resistance (for tantalum capacitors), mechanical influences and humidity the FIT figure can recalculated with acceleration factors standardized for industrial or military contexts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The higher the temperature and the applied voltage, the higher the failure rate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It is good to know that for capacitors with solid electrolytes the failure rate is often expressed as per cent failed components per thousand hours (n %/1000 h), and specified at reference conditions 85 °C and rated voltage UR.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] That is, "n" number of failed components per 105 hours, or in FIT the ten-thousand-fold value per 109 hours but for different reference conditions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For these other conditions the "%I1000 h" figure can be recalculated with acceleration factors standardized for industrial or military contexts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Most modern aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes nowadays are very reliable components with very low failure rates, with predicted life expectancies of decades under normal conditions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It is best practice to have electrolytic capacitors pass a post-forming process step after production, similar to a "burn in, so that early failures are eliminated during production.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The FIT values given in data sheets are calculated from the long-time experience of the manufacturer, based on the lifetime test results.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Typical reference failure rate values for aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes are for low voltages types (6.3–160 V) FIT rates in the range of 1 to 20 FIT and for high voltage types (>160–550 V) FIT rates in the range of 20 to 200 FIT.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Field failure rates for aluminum capacitors are in the range of 0.5 to 20 FIT.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The data for the "failure rate" specification are based on the results of lifetime testing (endurance testing).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In addition a "field failure rate" is sometimes specified.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This figures comes from big customers that noticed failures in the field out of their application.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Field failure rates could have much lower values.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For aluminum electrolytic capacitors they are in the range of 0.5 to 20 FIT.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The field failure rate values are in line with the usual orders of magnitude for electronic components.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes have an exceptional position among electronic components because they work with an electrolyte as liquid ingredient.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The liquid electrolyte determines the time-dependent behavior of electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] They age over time as the electrolyte evaporates.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This also implies that there is a sharp decline in useful lifespan with increasing temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] As a rule of thumb, every 10 degrees rise halves the useful life span.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This very slow drying-out of the electrolyte depends on the series construction, ambient temperature, voltage and ripple current load.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Lowering the electrolyte over time influences the capacitance, impedance and ESR of the capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The capacitance decreases and impedance and ESR increases with decreasing amounts of electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The leakage current decreases because all weaknesses are healed after the long forming time.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In contrast to electrolytic capacitors with solid electrolytes, "wet" electrolytic capacitors have an "end of life" when the components reach specified maximum changes of capacitance, impedance or ESR.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The time period to the "end of life" is called the "lifetime", "useful life", "load life" or "service life".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It represents the time of constant failure rate in the failure rate bathtub curve.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Under normal ambient conditions electrolytic capacitors can have more than a 15-year lifetime, but this can be limited depending on the degradation behavior of the rubber bung (which is not typically aged during lifetime testing).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This rating is tested with an accelerated aging test called an "endurance test" according to IEC 60384-4-1 with rated voltage at the upper category temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] One of the challenges with this aging test is the time required to extract any meaningful results.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In response to demands for long life, high temperature performance from automotive and green energy applications (solar microvinverters, LEDs, wind turbines, etc.), some capacitors require more than a year's worth of testing (10000 hours) before they can be qualified.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Due to this limitation, there has been increasing interest in methodologies to accelerate the test in a manner that still produces relevant results.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The graph at right show the behavior of the electrical parameters of aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes due to evaporation of the electrolyte in a 2000 h endurance test at 105 °C.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The process of drying out is also detectable by weight loss.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Parameters of the tested component beyond these limits can be counted as evidence of degradation failure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The testing time and temperature depend on the tested series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] That is the reason for the many different lifetime specifications in the data sheets of manufacturers, which are given in the form of a time/temperature indication, for example: 2000 h/85 °C, 2000 h/105 °C, 5000 h/105 °C, 2000 h/125 °C.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This figures specifies the minimum lifetime of the capacitors of a series, when exposed at the maximum temperature with applied rated voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Referring to the endurance test, this specification does not include the capacitors' being loaded with the rated ripple current value.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] But the additional internal heat of 3 to 10 K, depending on the series, which is generated by the ripple current is usually taken into account by the manufacturer due to safety margins when interpreting the results of its endurance tests.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] A test with an actual applied ripple current is affordable for any manufacturer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] A capacitor's lifetime for different operational conditions can be estimated using special formulas or graphs specified in the data sheets of serious manufacturers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] They use different ways achieve the specification; some provide special formulas, others specify their capacitor lifetime calculation with graphs that take into account the influence of applied voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The basic principle for calculating the time under operational conditions is the so-called "10-degree-rule".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This rule is also well known as the Arrhenius rule.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] It characterizes the change of thermic reaction speed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For every 10 °C lower temperature, evaporation halves.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] That means for every 10 °C lower temperature the lifetime of capacitors doubles.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If a lifetime specification of an electrolytic capacitor is, for example, 2000 h/105 °C, the capacitor's lifetime at 45 °C can be "calculated" as 128,000 hours—roughly 15 years—by using the 10-degree-rule.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Although the result of the longer lifetime at lower temperatures comes from a mathematical calculation, the result is always an estimation of the expected behavior of a group of similar components.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The lifetime of electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes depends on the evaporations rate and therefore on the core temperature of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This core temperature on the other hand depends on the ripple current load.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Using the 10-degree-rule with the capacitor case temperature gives a good approach to operational conditions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In case of higher ripple currents the lifetime could be influenced positively with force cooling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Near the end of the capacitor's lifetime degradation failure begins to appear.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] At the same time the range of the constant failure rate ends.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] But even after exceeding the capacitor's specified end of life the electronic circuit is not in immediate danger; only the functionality of the capacitor is reduced.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] With today's high levels of purity in the manufacture of electrolytic capacitors it is not to be expected that short circuits occur after the end-of-life-point with progressive evaporation combined with parameter degradation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes have, in terms of quality, a relatively negative public image.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This is contrary to industrial experience, where electrolytic capacitors are considered to be reliable components if used within their specified specifications during the calculated lifetime.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The negative public image might be, among other reasons, because failed electrolytic capacitors in devices are easily and immediately visible.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This is exceptional and not the case with other electronic components.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] As with any industrial product, specific causes of failure modes are known for aluminum electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolytes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] They can be differentiated in failures causes by capacitor development and production, by device production, by capacitor application or by external influences during use.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The capacitor manufacturing industries can only influence the first failure mode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Most manufacturers have had well-structured quality control departments for decades, supervising all development and manufacturing steps.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Failure mode flow charts demonstrate this.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] However, a typical physically or chemically caused major failure mode during application, like "field crystallization" for tantalum capacitors, is not known for non-solid aluminum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In many quarters, electrolytic capacitors are considered very unreliable components when compared to other passives.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This is partly a function of the history of these components.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Capacitors manufactured during and before World War II sometimes suffered from contamination during manual manufacturing, and in particular chlorine salts were often the reason for corrosive processes leading to high leakage currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Chlorine acts on aluminum as a catalyst for the formation of unstable oxide without becoming chemically bound itself.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] After World War II this problem was known but the measuring equipment was not accurate enough to detect chlorine in very low ppm concentration.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The situation improved over the next 20 years and the capacitors became good enough for longer life applications.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This leads in turn to a previously unnoticed water driven corrosion, which weakens the stable dielectric oxide layer during storage or disuse.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This leads to high leakage currents after storage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Most of the electrolytes in that time contain water, and many of the capacitors reach their end of life by drying out.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Water driven corrosion was the reason for recommended precondition instructions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The first solution in the 1970s was the development of water-free electrolyte systems based on organic solvents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Such halogen solutions sometimes permeate the seal of a capacitor and initiate chlorine corrosion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Again there was a leakage current problem.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The use of CFCs as solvents for dry cleaning have been phased out, for example, by the IPPC directive on greenhouse gases in 1994 and by the volatile organic compounds (VOC) directive of the EU in 1997.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In the meantime electrolytic systems have been developed with additives to inhibit the reaction between anodic aluminum oxide and water, which solve most of the high leakage current problems after storage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The ability of non-solid aluminum electrolytic capacitors to have a stable behavior during longer storage times can be tested using an accelerating test of storing the capacitor at its upper category temperature for a certain period, usually 1000 hours, without voltage applied.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] This "shelf life test" is a good indicator for an inert chemical behavior of the electrolytic system against the dielectric aluminum oxide layer because all chemical reactions are accelerated by high temperatures.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Nearly all today's series of capacitors fulfill the 1000 hours shelf life test, which is equivalent to a minimum five years of storage at room temperature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Modern electrolytic capacitors do not need preconditioning after such storage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] However, many capacitor series are specified only for two years storage time, but the limit is set by oxidation of terminals and resulting solderability problems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For restoring antique radio equipment using older electrolytic capacitors built in the 1970s or earlier, "pre-conditioning" is often recommended.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For this purpose, the rated voltage is applied to the capacitor via a series resistance of approximately 1 kΩ for a period of one hour.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Applying a voltage via a safety resistor repairs the oxide layer by self-healing, but slowly, minimizing internal heating.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] If capacitors still do not meet the leakage current requirements after preconditioning, it may be an indication of permanent damage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Smaller or low voltage aluminum electrolytic capacitors may be connected in parallel without any safety correction action.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Large sizes capacitors, especially large sizes and high voltage types, should be individually guarded against sudden energy charge of the whole capacitor bank due to a failed specimen.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Some applications like AC/AC converters with DC-link for frequency controls in three-phase grids need higher voltages than electrolytic capacitors usually offer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] For such applications electrolytic capacitors can be connected in series for increased voltage-withstanding capability.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] During charging, the voltage across each of the capacitors connected in series is proportional to the inverse of the individual capacitor's leakage current.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Since every capacitor differs somewhat in individual leakage current, the capacitors with a higher leakage current will get less voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The voltage balance over the series-connected capacitors is not symmetrical.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Passive or active voltage balance has to be provided in order to stabilize the voltage over each individual capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Electrolytic capacitors, like most other electronic components, have imprinted markings to indicate the manufacturer, the type, the electrical and thermal characteristics, and the date of manufacture.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Smaller capacitors use a shorthand notation to display all the relevant information in the limited space available.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The most commonly used format is: XYZ K/M VOLTS V, where XYZ represents the capacitance in μF, the letters K or M indicate the tolerance (±10% and ±20% respectively), and VOLTS V represents the rated voltage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Capacitance, tolerance, and date of manufacture can also be identified with a short code according to IEC 60062.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The date of manufacture is often printed in accordance with international standards in abbreviated form.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] SMD style electrolytic capacitors with non-solid electrolyte (vertical-chips, V-chips) have a colored filled half circle or a minus bar on the top case side visible to indicate the minus terminal side.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Additionally, the insulating plate under the capacitor body uses two skewed edges to indicate that the negative terminal is on the complement position.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Radial or single-ended electrolytic capacitors have a bar across the side of the capacitor to indicate the negative terminal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The negative terminal lead may be shorter than the positive terminal lead (similar to LEDs).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In addition, the negative terminal may have a knurled surface stamped on the top of the connecting lug.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] Axial electrolytic capacitor styles have a bar across or around the case pointing to the negative lead end to indicate the negative terminal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The positive terminal of the capacitor is on the side of the sealing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The negative terminal lead is shorter than the positive terminal lead.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] On a printed circuit board it is customary to indicate the correct orientation by using a square through-hole pad for the positive lead and a round pad for the negative one.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The standardization for all electrical, electronic components and related technologies follows the rules given by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), a non-profit, non-governmental international standards organization.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] The market for aluminum electrolytic capacitors in 2010 was around US$3.9 billion (approximately €2.9 billion), about 22% of the value of the total capacitor market of approximately US$18 billion (2008).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-electrolytic-capacitor-p02] In number of pieces these capacitors cover about 6% of the total capacitor market of some 70 to 80 billion pieces.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] An **electrolytic capacitor** is a polarized capacitor whose anode or positive plate is made of a metal that forms an insulating oxide layer through anodization.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This oxide layer acts as the dielectric of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] A solid, liquid, or gel electrolyte covers the surface of this oxide layer, serving as the cathode or negative plate of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Because of their very thin dielectric oxide layer and enlarged anode surface, electrolytic capacitors have a much higher capacitance-voltage (CV) product per unit volume than ceramic capacitors or film capacitors, and so can have large capacitance values.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] There are three families of electrolytic capacitor: aluminium electrolytic capacitors, tantalum electrolytic capacitors, and niobium electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The large capacitance of electrolytic capacitors makes them particularly suitable for passing or bypassing low-frequency signals, and for storing large amounts of energy.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] They are widely used for decoupling or noise filtering in power supplies and DC link circuits for variable-frequency drives, for coupling signals between amplifier stages, and storing energy as in a flashlamp.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are polarized components because of their asymmetrical construction and must be operated with a higher potential (i.e., more positive) on the anode than on the cathode at all times.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] For this reason the polarity is marked on the device housing.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Applying a reverse polarity voltage, or a voltage exceeding the maximum rated working voltage of as little as 1 or 1.5 volts, can damage the dielectric causing catastrophic failure of the capacitor itself.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Failure of electrolytic capacitors can result in an explosion or fire, potentially causing damage to other components as well as injuries.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Bipolar electrolytic capacitors which may be operated with either polarity are also made, using special constructions with two anodes connected in series.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] A bipolar electrolytic capacitor can be made by connecting two normal electrolytic capacitors in series, anode to anode or cathode to cathode, along with diodes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] As to the basic construction principles of electrolytic capacitors, there are three different types: aluminium, tantalum, and niobium capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Each of these three capacitor families uses non-solid and solid manganese dioxide or solid polymer electrolytes, so a great spread of different combinations of anode material and solid or non-solid electrolytes is available.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Like other conventional capacitors, electrolytic capacitors store the electric energy statically by charge separation in an electric field in the dielectric oxide layer between two electrodes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The non-solid or solid electrolyte in principle is the cathode, which thus forms the second electrode of the capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This and the storage principle distinguish them from electrochemical capacitors or supercapacitors, in which the electrolyte generally is the ionic conductive connection between two electrodes and the storage occurs with statically double-layer capacitance and electrochemical pseudocapacitance.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors use a chemical feature of some special metals, previously called "valve metals", which on contact with a particular electrolyte form a very thin insulating oxide layer on their surface by anodic oxidation which can function as a dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Niobium electrolytic capacitors use a sintered "slug" of high-purity niobium or niobium oxide powder with niobium pentoxide as dielectric.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] To increase their capacitance per unit volume, all anode materials are either etched or sintered and have a rough surface structure with a much higher surface area compared to a smooth surface of the same area or the same volume.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] By applying a positive voltage to the above-mentioned anode material in an electrolytic bath an oxide barrier layer with a thickness corresponding to the applied voltage will be formed (formation).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] After forming a dielectric oxide on the rough anode structure, a counter electrode has to match the rough insulating oxide surface.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This is accomplished by the electrolyte, which acts as the cathode electrode of an electrolytic capacitor.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] There are many different electrolytes in use.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Generally they are distinguished into two species, “non-solid” and “solid” electrolytes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] As a liquid medium which has ion conductivity caused by moving ions, non-solid electrolytes can easily fit the rough structures.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Solid electrolytes which have electron conductivity can fit the rough structures with the help of special chemical processes like pyrolysis for manganese dioxide or polymerization for conducting polymers.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Comparing the permittivities of the different oxide materials it is seen that tantalum pentoxide has a permittivity approximately three times higher than aluminium oxide.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Tantalum electrolytic capacitors of a given capacitance-voltage (CV) product value theoretically are therefore smaller than aluminium electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] In practice different safety margins to reach reliable components makes a comparison difficult.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The anodically generated insulating oxide layer is destroyed if the polarity of the applied voltage changes.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] Electrolytic capacitors are based on the principle of a "plate capacitor" whose capacitance increases with larger electrode area A, higher dielectric permittivity ε, and thinness of dielectric (d).
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The dielectric thickness of electrolytic capacitors is very small, in the range of nanometers per volt.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] On the other hand, the voltage strengths of these oxide layers are quite high.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] With this very thin dielectric oxide layer combined with a sufficiently high dielectric strength the electrolytic capacitors can achieve a high volumetric capacitance.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] This is one reason for the high capacitance values of electrolytic capacitors compared to conventional capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] All etched or sintered anodes have a much higher surface area compared to a smooth surface of the same area or the same volume.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] That increases the capacitance value, depending on the rated voltage, by a factor of up to 200 for non-solid aluminium electrolytic capacitors as well as for solid tantalum electrolytic capacitors.
[src:electrolytic-capacitor/electrolytic-capacitor-p01] The large surface compared to a smooth one is the second reason for the relatively high capacitance values of electrolytic capacitors compared with other capacitor families.
